    <section class="consulting-block consulting-block--lead" id="what-i-do" data-label="What I do" aria-labelledby="what-i-do-heading">
      <div class="consulting-block-copy">
        <h2 class="consulting-block-eyebrow" id="what-i-do-heading">What I do</h2>

        <p>Most global health programs run two versions of themselves: the one in the reporting documents, and the one being delivered at the door. The two versions do not always agree, and in most programs no one is responsible for closing the gap between them. Programs end up defending the reporting version, because the reporting version is what gets audited &ndash; even when the field has quietly worked out something better.</p>

        <p>I work between those two versions.</p>

        <p>I read the program as it is actually delivered, render that reading in language the institution can act on, and help the team build the social processes that let field-level knowledge legitimately revise the official frame without breaking the funding model. The methods I draw on most often &ndash; <em>Brokered Design</em> and <em>Brokered Dialogue</em>, developed over the last seven years with Jim Lavery &ndash; are structured ways of brokering insight between stakeholder groups who would not otherwise be able to revise each other&rsquo;s positions.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="consulting-block" id="getting-started" data-label="Getting Started" aria-labelledby="getting-started-heading">
      <div class="consulting-block-copy">
        <h2 class="consulting-block-eyebrow" id="getting-started-heading">Getting Started</h2>

        <p>If you would like to work together, send me a short or long note about the problem you&rsquo;re working on. Email or DM is fine. I&rsquo;ll ask follow-up questions to figure out whether I can be useful before either of us puts time or money down. The more context you share, the better I can dig in beforehand, and the more useful our first call will be.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="consulting-block consulting-arrangement" id="what-to-expect" data-label="Working with me: What to expect" aria-labelledby="what-to-expect-heading">
      <div class="consulting-block-copy">
        <h2 class="consulting-block-eyebrow" id="what-to-expect-heading">Working with me: What to expect</h2>

        <p>Most engagements start with a paid &ldquo;thought sparring&rdquo; conversation: <span class="consulting-price">$350 for a 60&ndash;90 minute call.</span> I send a few prep questions a day or two ahead. The purpose of the call is for me to better understand the situation and figure out the next useful move, while giving you a sense of whether you&rsquo;re <a class="consulting-quiet-link" href="https://stephango.com/in-good-hands">in good hands</a>.</p>

        <p>I only book the call if I&rsquo;m confident I can deliver more than $350 in value to you. If I can&rsquo;t, I&rsquo;ll tell you, and where I can, point you to someone who fits better.</p>

        <p>If $350 is too much, write anyway. Depending on your situation, there&rsquo;s flexibility on rate for early-stage or public-interest work.</p>

        <p>Beyond the first call, scope and rate are discussed and agreed in writing.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="consulting-more-knots" id="recurring-problems-section" aria-labelledby="recurring-problems-heading">
      <div class="consulting-block-copy">
        <h2 class="consulting-block-eyebrow" id="recurring-problems-heading">Recurring problems</h2>

        <p>This work falls into a few recurring shapes. The named problems below are drawn from established consulting literature &ndash; Edgar Schein, Gerald Weinberg, and others &ndash; that names the dysfunctions practitioners actually run into. Each entry pairs the concept with an engagement from my own record.</p>

        <h3 class="consulting-subhead" id="frameworks-subhead">A note on frameworks</h3>

        <p>&ldquo;Wicked problems&rdquo; is a frame for hard problems. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/14494035.2019.1617971">The term has been used too many ways to mean much</a>. Once I&rsquo;ve called a problem wicked, I know it is hard. I do not know what kind of hard, or what to do next.</p>

        <p>Frameworks &ndash; VUCA, wicked, whatever is current &ndash; are useful for talking about problems. They are less useful for working through them. The specifics of any particular program are always more granular than the label that gets applied to it.</p>

        <h3 class="consulting-subhead" id="problem-examples">Examples from past work</h3>

        <h4 class="consulting-knot-name">The presenting problem vs. the real problem.</h4>
        <p class="consulting-knot-attribution"><em>Schein, Humble Consulting (2016).</em></p>

        <p>What the client says they need help with rarely matches what is actually worrying them. The presented version is usually accurate as far as it goes; it is also usually the version that has been approved upward, written into reporting cycles, and rehearsed enough times to sound complete. The real concern tends to surface later, after enough relationship has been built that the client can risk saying it out loud, or after the data the project produces starts to contradict the framing the project was funded under.</p>

        <p><em>Haiti, 2019&ndash;2023.</em> The Carter Center&rsquo;s LF-MDA program in L&eacute;og&acirc;ne and Gressier presented the problem as persistent non-compliance: a roughly 35% residual share of the population that consistently did not participate in annual MDA campaigns. The standard interpretation &ndash; fear of side effects, rumor, religious concerns &ndash; was almost certainly true for some subset, and the program had invested considerably in addressing it. But the co-production interviews surfaced a different pattern: a substantial fraction of the people who satisfied the program&rsquo;s operational definition of non-compliance (i.e., 0 or 1 participation across the prior five rounds) had been willing to participate and had not been reached. The post had run out of pills before they arrived; the team had moved through their neighborhood faster than residents could respond; or canvassing happened during working hours and no one was home to answer the door. The cut, in practice, was disaggregating &ldquo;non-compliance&rdquo; into access-bounded and refusal-bounded sub-types, each requiring different operational adjustments (i.e., stock-flow planning and team routing on one side, motivational communication and trust work on the other).</p>

        <h4 class="consulting-knot-name">The Label Law.</h4>
        <p class="consulting-knot-attribution"><em>Weinberg, More Secrets of Consulting (2002).</em></p>

        <p>A word like &ldquo;effective&rdquo; is a label, not a measurement. The label can be carried through years of reporting, budget narratives, and donor language without ever being given a definition that two people would agree on. Once an evaluation tries to use the label to compare programs or guide investment, the gap shows up as running disagreement about whether anything has actually been measured.</p>

        <p><em>Atlanta, 2023.</em> The Health Campaign Effectiveness Coalition&rsquo;s Knowledge Architecture project worked from UNICEF&rsquo;s eleven parameters of effectiveness &ndash; equity, coverage, integration, sustainability, and so on. Each parameter was unspecified across country programs (i.e., country teams reading the same word meant different operational things by it, and the coalition could not assemble cross-program lessons without first deciding which version of the word it was tracking). The work was less about scoring programs than about asking each team to write down what they actually counted when they said &ldquo;equity&rdquo; in a given campaign &ndash; whose participation, measured against which denominator, with what disaggregation. The output was a structured vocabulary that let country evidence flow upward without losing the operational specifics that made the word meaningful in the first place.</p>

        <h4 class="consulting-knot-name">Reward-system mismatch.</h4>
        <p class="consulting-knot-attribution"><em>Schein, Humble Consulting (2016); cf. Weinberg&rsquo;s Hardware Store Fallacy.</em></p>

        <p>What an organization writes down about how it works and what the day-to-day reward structure pushes people to do are usually two different things. Training manuals, supervisor expectations, and informal social rewards form a stack, and the stack is rarely consistent. Frontline staff act on the layer that pays them &ndash; in money, in standing, or in being left alone &ndash; not on the layer that gets cited in policy documents.</p>

        <p><em>Haiti, 2019&ndash;2023.</em> The Carter Center&rsquo;s drug-distributor protocol described a deliberate, household-by-household process: knock, explain, dose, log, return to absent households the same day. Distributor interviews described something else. Supervisor checks were timed against territory completion (i.e., how many houses had been logged by mid-afternoon), and team-level performance ratings rolled up from those tallies. The manual asked for a clinical encounter at every door; the timesheet rewarded sweeping the route. Distributors made the trade-off the reward system asked for &ndash; faster passes, fewer return visits, more &ldquo;not home&rdquo; logged as final &ndash; and the residual non-compliance the program was trying to explain was partly produced by its own throughput metrics. Naming the mismatch was the first move; redesigning the supervisor check sheet was the second.</p>

        <h4 class="consulting-knot-name">Behavioral paralysis.</h4>
        <p class="consulting-knot-attribution"><em>Schein, Humble Consulting (2016), ch. 5&ndash;6.</em></p>

        <p>An organization can know what is wrong, name it openly in private, and still be unable to move. The block is usually social rather than analytic: changing the behavior would require someone to absorb a cost that no individual is positioned to absorb, and the routine that everyone privately doubts gets defended in meetings because defending it is cheaper than the alternative. The diagnostic giveaway is the gap between hallway conversation and minuted decisions.</p>

        <p><em>Emory.</em> A Brokered Dialogue engagement around gene drive governance &ndash; convened with Jim Lavery under an IRB-approved protocol &ndash; brought together stakeholders whose positions on the technology had hardened over a decade of public debate. Each side could anticipate the other&rsquo;s arguments, which meant most encounters produced restatements rather than movement. The dialogue method used asynchronous, edited video exchange (i.e., each participant&rsquo;s response was filmed in private, transcribed, and shared with the next participant before they responded) so that the social pressure of a live room was removed from the part of the conversation where people decided what they thought. The structure did not resolve the underlying disagreements. It produced something the field had not previously had: a record of each participant&rsquo;s reasoning that the others recognized as fair, which made it possible to discuss what to do next without first re-litigating who was acting in good faith.</p>

        <h4 class="consulting-knot-name">The Five-Minute Rule.</h4>
        <p class="consulting-knot-attribution"><em>Weinberg, Secrets of Consulting (1985).</em></p>

        <p>Clients almost always know the answer to the problem they are asking about. The answer typically arrives in the first few minutes of the first real conversation, embedded in a story or an aside that the speaker treats as too obvious to count as an insight. The consultant&rsquo;s job at that stage is recognition &ndash; hearing the answer when it goes by, naming it back to the speaker in a form they can act on, and resisting the urge to add to it before the person who said it has had a chance to recognize it as theirs.</p>

        <p><em>Haiti, 2019.</em> The first round of distributor interviews under what became Brokered Design surfaced the answer in the first afternoon. The drug distributors knew, in concrete detail, which workarounds were producing most of the coverage the program was reporting &ndash; informal handoffs to neighbors, second passes by individual team members on their own time, household-level deals about who would dose whom. These workarounds were already doing the work; they had simply never been written into the protocol, partly because no one had asked, and partly because writing them down might surface things the program officially could not endorse. The cut was elevating the workarounds into named practices, attaching them to the formal protocol, and letting the team keep doing what was already working without having to do it invisibly.</p>

        <h4 class="consulting-knot-name">Boulding&rsquo;s Backward Basis.</h4>
        <p class="consulting-knot-attribution"><em>Kenneth Boulding, via Weinberg, Secrets of Consulting (1985).</em></p>

        <p>&ldquo;Things are the way they are because they got that way.&rdquo; A program&rsquo;s current shape is almost always the rational residue of decisions that made sense at the time each was made, given what was known then and what the previous round had just taught. Treating the current state as evidence of present incompetence misses the path; treating it as evidence of a settled equilibrium misses the learning. The useful move is to recover the sequence &ndash; what changed, when, in response to what &ndash; before recommending what to change next.</p>

        <p><em>Haiti, 2007&ndash;2023.</em> The Carter Center&rsquo;s LF-MDA program in L&eacute;og&acirc;ne and Gressier had completed seventeen annual rounds by the time the co-production work began. Each round&rsquo;s operational choices &ndash; canvassing routes, distributor recruitment, communication strategy, supervisor ratios &ndash; were legible only in light of what the prior round had surfaced (i.e., a routing change in year nine was a response to a stockout pattern noticed in year seven; a communications shift in year twelve was a response to a rumor cycle from year ten). Reading the program as a stack of rational adjustments rather than a fixed protocol changed what counted as a useful recommendation. The team did not need a new manual; it needed the next legible adjustment, made in the same idiom the prior sixteen had been made in, so that the seventeenth round&rsquo;s answers could be carried forward into the eighteenth without restarting the institutional memory.</p>
      </div>
